  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3114328969" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3114328969" />
    <a title="Lindsey Goddard" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9488733-lindsey-goddard"><img alt="Lindsey Goddard" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1620390529p2/9488733.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3114328969?book_show_action=true">Feb 16, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lindsey Goddard" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lindsey Goddard" href="/user/show/9488733-lindsey-goddard">Lindsey Goddard</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3114328969" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13262120354337042960">This novel follows Clive Barker&apos;s usual concept of &quot;worlds within worlds&quot;, as I like to describe it. There is a place called Quiddity, a dream-like sea filled with strange islands, where every human visits three times in their life - at birth, at death, and at the moment we find our true love and sleep next to them for the first time. One man, Randolph Jaffe, is determined to find answers after catching hints and clues of Quiddity in his boring adult life. He tracks down an ambitious scientist w</span>
  <span id="freeText13262120354337042960" style="display:none">This novel follows Clive Barker's usual concept of "worlds within worlds", as I like to describe it. There is a place called Quiddity, a dream-like sea filled with strange islands, where every human visits three times in their life - at birth, at death, and at the moment we find our true love and sleep next to them for the first time. One man, Randolph Jaffe, is determined to find answers after catching hints and clues of Quiddity in his boring adult life. He tracks down an ambitious scientist who has been ostracized from the scientific community. Their goal? To create a portal to Quiddity. Though the pair succeed in doing this, they are transformed from mere humans into something else, something godlike, and they begin battling over whether or not this door to another realm should be opened. After many years, it is opened by Jaffe... and Quiddity is slowly but surely leaking into the human world and unleashing all sorts of nightmares. A race of beings called the Iad Uroboros are ready to enter our realm. Humanity will not survive. They must be stopped.<br /><br />Barker has said that this book was very difficult to write, and I see why. He piles theme upon theme as the story develops, all of which must meet some conclusion. There are a ton of different elements to this tale, and it can be somewhat of a chore for the reader to keep track of everything. But all in all, I found this book very enchanting. My only complaint is that I would've liked to see a few of the main characters developed more, but there are so many characters at play here, it would have required several more pages to expand on them, and I was tired at the end of this book as it is. So maybe Barker had his reasons. <br /><br />I like that the villain is not ALL villain. He retains some of the emotion and compassion from his former human self, which becomes essential to the plot. The two lovebirds in this story, Howard and Jo-Beth, were not developed enough for me to care about their love, but that is okay with me. I did not select this book with the intention of reading Romance. And there is a much darker, more disturbing love story from Jo-Beth's twin, Tommy-Ray's, point of view, which I found to be a nice touch, adding to the suspense and horror here.<br /><br />I often say that Clive Barker would be better categorized under "horror fantasy" than simply "horror" or "fantasy". His stories are fantastical, and this one is especially so. He writes like no other. His novels are much like a hallucinogenic trip, or a swim through a sea of dreams. I feel like I visited Quiddity. I'll not soon forget this book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13262120354337042960" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


